\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. B. alba} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 1012 (1753). Dioecious in S.E. Europe, elsewhere monoecious. Stems up to 4 m, branched. Leaves 5-10 cm, ovate, cordate, 5-angled or palmately 5-lobed; lobes ovate or triangular, acute or acuminate, sharply dentate, the central much longer than the lateral. Calyx of female flowers usually as long as the corolla. Stigma glabrous. Fruit 7-8 mm in diameter, black. {\i S., C. & E. Europe; formerly cultivated as a medicinal plant and often naturalized further north and west.} Al Au Bu Ge Gr He Hu It Ju Po Rm Rs (C, W, K, E) Tu [Be Cz Da Fe Ga No Rs (B) Su].
